Abstract

This study develops predictive models to identify customers likely to churn using a dataset of 5,000 customers. Class imbalance is addressed via weighting and sampling techniques. Recursive feature elimination identifies 13 key predictors, with daytime usage variables being most influential. A weighted random forest model achieves 86.7% F1 score and 89.9% balanced accuracy. Recommendations include focusing on daytime usage patterns, improving customer service, and minimizing attention on less impactful variables. The analysis demonstrates effective churn prediction using machine learning, with the proposed model and retention strategies potentially guiding customer retention efforts.

Introduction

Customer retention is crucial for telecom companies to maintain revenue streams and profitability. However, with increasing competition, retaining customers has become challenging. To develop effective customer retention strategies, it is critical to understand the key drivers of customer churn.

This report presents an analysis of customer data, with a focus on 18 characteristics:

  • churn
  • accountlength
  • internationalplan
  • voicemailplan
  • numbervmailmessages
  • totaldayminutes
  • totaldaycalls
  • totaldaycharge
  • totaleveminutes
  • totalevecalls
  • totalevecharge
  • totalnightminutes
  • totalnightcalls
  • totalnightcharge
  • totalintlminutes
  • totalintlcalls
  • totalintlcharge
  • numbercustomerservicecalls

The objective of this report is to provide company leadership with actionable steps grounded in analytical insights to reduce customer churn

The df data frame contains information about 5,000 customers. It has 18 columns.The churn, internationalplan, and voicemailplan columns are of character data type. The remaining columns are of double data type, which is a numeric data type capable of storing decimal or floating-point numbers.

Here is a brief description of each column:

  • churn: Whether or not a customer has churned (i.e., left the company)
  • accountlength: The length of the customers account in days
  • internationalplan: Whether or not the customer has an international plan
  • voicemailplan: Whether or not the customer has a voicemail plan
  • numbervmailmessages: The number of voicemail messages the customer has
  • totaldayminutes: The total number of minutes the customer used during the day
  • totaldaycalls: The total number of calls the customer made during the day
  • totaldaycharge: The total charge for the customers day usage
  • totaleveminutes: The total number of minutes the customer used during the evening
  • totalevecalls: The total number of calls the customer made during the evening
  • totalevecharge: The total charge for the customers evening usage
  • totalnightminutes: The total number of minutes the customer used during the night
  • totalnightcalls: The total number of calls the customer made during the night
  • totalnightcharge: The total charge for the customers night usage
  • totalintlminutes: The total number of international minutes the customer used
  • totalintlcalls: The total number of international calls the customer made
  • totalintlcharge: The total charge for the customers international usage
  • numbercustomerservicecalls: The number of times the customer called customer service

Removing Duplicate Rows

remove_duplicates <- function(df) {
  # Find duplicated rows
  dup_rows <- duplicated(df) | duplicated(df, fromLast = TRUE)
  
  # If there are no duplicated rows, return the original data frame
  if (!any(dup_rows)) {
    cat("No duplicates found\n")
    return(df)
  }
  
  # Find the row indices of the duplicated rows
  dup_indices <- which(dup_rows)
  
  # Group the duplicated rows by their values
  groups <- split(dup_indices, apply(df[dup_rows, ], 1, paste, collapse = ""))
  
  # Print a message to inform the user that duplicate rows were found
  cat("Duplicate rows found at indices:\n")
  
  # For each group of duplicated rows
  for (group in groups) {
    # Sort the row indices in ascending order
    group <- sort(group)
    
    # Print the row indices of the duplicates
    cat(paste(group, collapse = ", "), "\n")
    
    # Keep the row with the lowest index and remove the rest
    df <- df[!duplicated(df), ]
  }
  
  return(df)
}
df <- remove_duplicates(df)
## No duplicates found


Analysis of the data frame has determined that no duplicate entries are present, indicating that each row is distinct and duplicate removal is not required.

Filtering and Selecting Variables with Low Unique Counts

diagnose(df) %>%

  select(variables)
## # A tibble: 4  1

##   <chr>                     
## 1 churn                     
## 2 internationalplan

## 4 numbercustomerservicecalls


The result indicates that there are four potentially categorical columns: churn, internationalplan, voicemailplan, and numbercustomerservicecalls.

The churn, internationalplan, and voicemailplan columns each have two unique values, while the numbercustomerservicecalls column has ten unique values.

Finding Unique Values in Selected Columns

lapply(df[ ,c("churn", 
             "internationalplan",

## $churn
## [1] "No"  "Yes"
## 
## $internationalplan
## [1] "no"  "yes"
## 
## $voicemailplan
## [1] "yes" "no" 
## 
## $numbercustomerservicecalls
##  [1] 1 0 2 3 4 5 7 9 6 8


From the result, it can be seen that:

  • The churn column contains two unique values: No and Yes. This suggests that the column is a binary variable indicating whether a customer has churned or not.

  • Similarly, the internationalplan and voicemailplan columns also contain two unique values: no and yes. These columns represent binary variables indicating whether a customer has subscribed to an international plan or a voicemail plan, respectively.

  • The numbercustomerservicecalls column contains 10 unique values ranging from 0 to 9. This suggests that the column is a numerical variable representing the number of customer service calls made by each customer.

Based on these observations, it can be concluded that the churn, internationalplan, and voicemailplan columns are categorical variables and should be converted to factors.

Splitting Data into Training and Test Sets

split_data <- function(data, size) {
  # Set the seed for random number generation
  set.seed(42)
  
  # Get the number of rows in the data
  n <- nrow(data)
  
  # Generate a random sample of row indices for the training data
  id <- sample(1:n, size = size * n)
  
  # Create the training data by selecting the rows with the sampled indices
  train_data <- data[id, ]
  
  # Create the test data by selecting the rows not in the training data
  test_data <- data[-id, ]
  
  # Return a list containing the training and test data
  list(train = train_data, test = test_data)
}
splitData <- split_data(df, 0.8)
train_data <- splitData$train
test_data <- splitData$test


The df dataframe is partitioned into training and testing datasets using an 80/20 split. 80% of the data is randomly allocated to the training dataset, while the remaining 20% is assigned to the testing dataset.

Running Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) to Select Predictive Variables

run_rfe <- function(data, response, functions, method = "cv", number) {
  # Set the seed for random number generation
  set.seed(12)

  # Define the control using the specified functions, method, and number
  control <- rfeControl(functions = functions, method = method, number = number)

  # Set sizes to 1:(ncol(data)-1)
  sizes <- c(1:(ncol(data)-1))

  # Run the RFE algorithm
  rfe_result <- rfe(data[, !names(data) %in% response],
                    data[[response]], sizes = sizes,
                    rfeControl = control)

  # Summarize results
  print(rfe_result)

}

Training Multiple Classification Models with Cross-Validation

# Set the seed for random number generation
set.seed(24)

# Set up the control parameters for the training process
ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", # Cross-validation method
                     number = 10, # Number of cross-validation folds
                     verboseIter = FALSE, # Do not print iteration log
                     classProbs = TRUE, # Compute class probabilities
                     summaryFunction = prSummary, # Summarize performance of model during resampling 
                     savePredictions = "final") # Save final predictions

# Define a list of algorithms to use
algorithmList <- c('rpart', 'glm', 'knn')

# Define a list of tuning parameters for the random forest algorithm
tune_List <- list(rf = caretModelSpec(method="rf",
                                      tuneGrid=data.frame(mtry=2:17)))

# Train multiple models using caretList function
orig_models <- caretList(churn ~ ., # Formula for the model
                     data=subset_train, # Training data
                     metric = "F", # Metric to optimize
                     trControl=ctrl, # Control parameters for training
                     methodList=algorithmList, # List of algorithms to use
                     tuneList=tune_List, # List of tuning parameters
                     preProcess = c("center", "scale")) # Preprocessing steps


This analysis utilizes the caret package to train a variety of machine learning models for the purpose of predicting a binary outcome variable, churn. A 10-fold cross-validation procedure is implemented for model training and evaluation, with the final predictions being saved. The models being trained include rpart (recursive partitioning and regression trees), glm (generalized linear models), and knn (k-nearest neighbors), as well as a random forest (rf) model with a specified tuning grid for the mtry parameter. The training data undergoes pre-processing through centering and scaling of the predictor variables. F is used as the performance metric for model selection.

train_performance <- function(sum_models_result) {
  metrics <- c("AUC", "F", "Precision", "Recall")

  # Initialize an empty dataframe
  df <- data.frame()

  # Loop through each metric and bind the results to the dataframe
  for(metric in metrics){
    temp_df <- data.frame(Model = names(sum_models_result$statistics[[metric]][,"Mean"]),
                          Metric = metric,
                          Mean = sum_models_result$statistics[[metric]][,"Mean"])
    df <- rbind(df, temp_df)
  }

  # Reshape the dataframe from long to wide format using the 'reshape()' function
  df_final <- reshape(df, idvar = "Model", timevar = "Metric", direction = "wide")

  # Remove row names
  row.names(df_final) <- NULL

  # Remove 'Mean.' prefix from column names
  names(df_final) <- gsub("Mean.", "", names(df_final))
  
  # Sort the dataframe by the "F" metric in descending order
  df_final <- df_final[order(df_final$F, decreasing = TRUE), ]

  # Return the final dataframe without row names
  return(df_final)
}
train_perform_orgi <- train_performance(orig_models_result_summary)


The train_performance function is applied to extract the principal performance metrics achieved by each model throughout the training phase. The outcomes, referred to as train_perform_orgi, are displayed in a structured table format. This table provides key performance metrics including "AUC", "F", "Precision", and "Recall" for each model.

Generating and Evaluating Predictions for Testing Multiple Models

generate_predictions <- function(models, test_data) {
  # Generate predictions for each model on the test dataset
  predictions <- lapply(names(models), function(model_name) {
    # Get the model object from the models list
    model <- models[[model_name]]
    
    # Use the predict function to generate predictions for the test dataset
    predicted <- predict(model, newdata = test_data)
    
    # Return the predictions
    predicted
  })
  
  # Set the names of the predictions list to match the names of the models
  names(predictions) <- names(models)
  
  # Return the list of predictions
  predictions
}
evaluate_predictions_df <- function(predictions, observed, positive) {
  # Calculate the performance metrics for each set of predictions
  metrics <- sapply(names(predictions), function(model_name) {
    # Get the predictions for the current model
    predicted <- predictions[[model_name]]
    
    # Calculate the confusion matrix for the current model's predictions
    cm <- confusionMatrix(predicted, observed, positive = positive, mode = "prec_recall")
    
    # Extract the performance metrics from the confusion matrix
    c(Accuracy = cm$overall["Accuracy"],
      F1 = cm$byClass["F1"],
      Precision = cm$byClass["Precision"],
      Recall = cm$byClass["Recall"])
  })
  
  # Create a data frame containing the model names and performance metrics
  df <- data.frame(Model = names(predictions), t(metrics))
  
  # Rename the columns to use shorter names
  colnames(df) <- c("Model", "Accuracy", "F1", "Precision", "Recall")
  
  # Sort the data frame by F1 score in descending order
  df <- df[order(df$F1, decreasing = TRUE), ]
  
  # Reset the row names of the data frame
  row.names(df) <- NULL
  
  # Return the resulting data frame
  df
}

Training Weighted Classification Models with Cross-Validation

# Calculate the weights for each class in the target variable 'churn'
model_weights <- ifelse(subset_train$churn == "Yes",
                        (1/table(subset_train$churn)[1]) * 0.5,
                        (1/table(subset_train$churn)[2]) * 0.5)

# Use the same seed to ensure same cross-validation splits
ctrl$seeds <- orig_models$control$seeds

# Build weighted models using caretList function
weighted_models <- caretList(churn ~ ., # Formula for the model
                     data=subset_train, # Training data
                     metric = "F", # Metric to optimize
                     trControl=ctrl, # Control parameters for training
                     methodList=algorithmList, # List of algorithms to use
                     tuneList=tune_List, # List of tuning parameters
                     preProcess = c("center", "scale"), # Preprocessing steps
                     weights = model_weights) # Weights for each class in the target variable


This analysis is an extension of the orig_models. It introduces a weighting mechanism to handle class imbalance in the target variable, churn. The weights are calculated such that instances of the "No" class are assigned a weight of (1/table(subset_train$churn)[1]) * 0.5, and instances of "Yes" class are assigned a weight of (1/table(subset_train$churn)[2]) * 0.5. This ensures that both classes have an equal total weight, which can help improve model performance when there is class imbalance.

The same seed is used to ensure consistency in cross-validation splits between the original and weighted models. The caretList function is then used again to train the models, this time with the addition of the weights argument. This argument takes the calculated weights and applies them during model training, effectively giving more importance to instances of the minority class. The models being trained remain the same as before - rpart, glm, knn, and rf - and they undergo the same pre-processing steps of centering and scaling. The performance metric for model selection continues to be F.

Training Down-Sampled Classification Models with Cross-Validation

# Use the same seed to ensure same cross-validation splits
ctrl$seeds <- orig_models$control$seeds

# Set the sampling method to 'down' in the control parameters
ctrl$sampling <- "down"

# Build down-sampled models using caretList function
down_models <- caretList(churn ~ ., # Formula for the model
                     data=subset_train, # Training data
                     metric = "F", # Metric to optimize
                     trControl=ctrl, # Control parameters for training
                     methodList=algorithmList, # List of algorithms to use
                     tuneList=tune_List, # List of tuning parameters
                     preProcess = c("center", "scale")) # Preprocessing steps


This analysis is an extension of the orig_models. The same seed is used to ensure identical cross-validation splits for model reproducibility. A new control parameter, sampling, is set to down to indicate the use of down-sampling, a technique often used to balance the classes in the training data. This is particularly useful when dealing with imbalanced datasets where one class significantly outnumbers the other.

The caretList function is then called again to train the models with the updated control parameters. The models being trained remain the same: rpart, glm, knn, and a random forest model with a specified tuning grid for the mtry parameter. The training data undergoes the same pre-processing steps of centering and scaling. The performance metric for model selection continues to be F. This process results in a new set of models, down_models, trained using down-sampling.

This is further corroborated in the testing phase, where randomForest_smote_test achieves the highest F1 score, reinforcing its superior performance.

In contrast, logistic_smote and logistic_smote_test register the lowest F and F1 scores respectively in both phases. This implies that these models may face challenges in effectively balancing precision and recall.

The knn_smote and decisionTree_smote models display moderate performance. Despite having lower F scores in the training phase compared to randomForest_smote, they still exhibit reasonable effectiveness.

In conclusion, these results suggest that for this specific task, the randomForest_smote model is likely to be the most effective choice given its superior performance in both training and testing phases. for this task.

Extracting Optimal Models Based on Training and Testing Performance Measures

get_best_models <- function(train_perform_list, test_perform_list, train_measure = "F", test_measure = "F1") {
  
  result_df <- data.frame()

  for(i in 1:length(train_perform_list)) {
    # Detect the highest test_measure from each test_perform and extract the test_measure values and Model value of that model
    max_test_measure <- test_perform_list[[i]][which.max(test_perform_list[[i]][[test_measure]]), c("Model", test_measure)]

    # Remove the '_test' suffix from the Model names
    max_test_measure$Model <- sub("_test$", "", max_test_measure$Model)

    # Match the model of the highest test_measure from each test_perform with the Model value of train_perform and extract the train_measure values and Model value of that model of train_perform
    match_train_measure <- train_perform_list[[i]][train_perform_list[[i]]$Model == max_test_measure$Model, c("Model", train_measure)]

    # Use the result to create a dataframe with 4 columns
    df <- data.frame(Train_Model = match_train_measure$Model, Train_Measure = match_train_measure[[train_measure]], Test_Model = paste0(max_test_measure$Model, "_test"), Test_Measure = max_test_measure[[test_measure]])

    # Append to result_df
    result_df <- rbind(result_df, df)
  }

  # Sort result_df by Test_Measure in descending order
  result_df <- result_df[order(-result_df$Test_Measure), ]

  return(result_df)
}

draw_confusion_matrix <- function(df, cm, y) {
  
  # Get the levels of the factor vector in the dataframe
  class <- levels(df[[y]])
  
  # Set up the layout of the plot

  # Create the confusion matrix 
  rect(150, 430, 240, 370, col='#32CD32') # True Positive box
  text(195, 435, class[1], cex=1.2) # Label for True Positive box
  rect(250, 430, 340, 370, col='#8B0000') # False Negative box
  text(295, 435, class[2], cex=1.2) # Label for False Negative box
  text(125, 370, 'Predicted', cex=1.3, srt=90, font=2) # Label for Predicted classes
  text(245, 450, 'Actual', cex=1.3, font=2) # Label for Actual classes
  rect(150, 305, 240, 365, col='#8B0000') # False Positive box
  rect(250, 305, 340, 365, col='#32CD32') # True Negative box
  text(140, 400, class[1], cex=1.2, srt=90) # Label for Actual Positive class
  text(140, 335, class[2], cex=1.2, srt=90) # Label for Actual Negative class

  # Add in the confusion matrix results  
  res <- as.numeric(cm$table)
  
  # Add in the confusion matrix results to each box
  text(195, 400, res[1], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white') # True Positive result
  text(195, 335, res[2], cex=1.6, font=2, col='white') # False Positive result

Conclusion and Recommendations

The analysis of the customer dataset provides several key insights and evaluates the performance of various predictive models. The dataset, which contains information about 5,000 customers across 18 variables, identifies churn as the target variable. A significant imbalance is observed in the churn variable, with a larger number of customers retaining their subscription compared to those who discontinue their service.

To address this imbalance, different models apply various techniques, including weighting mechanisms, up-sampling, down-sampling, and Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique (SMOTE). Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) is used for feature selection, identifying 13 key variables as crucial predictors of customer churn.

The randomForest_w model outperforms all others. This model uses a weighting mechanism to handle class imbalance and shows excellent performance on both training and test sets. It achieves an F1 score of 86.7% and a balanced accuracy of 89.9%, considering the imbalanced dataset. The models robust performance in correctly classifying instances is reflected in a Kappa statistic of 84.6%.

Based on these insights, the following recommendations are proposed:

  1. Focus on Daytime Usage: As totaldayminutes and totaldaycharge are the most influential variables, focusing on customers daytime usage patterns could be beneficial. Offering tailored packages or discounts during the day might help retain customers.

  2. Improve Customer Service: The numbercustomerservicecalls variable is a significant predictor of churn. This suggests that customers who make more service calls are more likely to churn. Therefore, improving customer service quality and resolving issues promptly could reduce the number of service calls and potentially decrease churn.

  3. Less Significant Variables: Variables like voicemailplanyes and numbervmailmessages have minimal impact on the models predictions. While these features shouldnt be ignored, they might not require as much attention in retention strategies.
